# Pre-restructure fossils (root-level Python modules from before apps/ + config/
# layout). These do NOT exist in git, but they have re-appeared on the VPS host
# (/opt/labcontrol/) at least twice (2026-05-05 cleanup + 2026-05-06 redeploy).
# Dockerfile uses `COPY . .`, so without these excludes a fossil /app/celery.py
# would shadow the `celery` Python package and crash gunicorn at boot.
# Until Dockerfile is migrated to a whitelist `COPY apps/ ./apps/` style, keep
# these explicit:
/celery.py
/urls.py
/wsgi.py
/asgi.py
/admin.py
/__init__.py

# Root-level app DIRECTORIES — same fossil class as the .py files above. They
# get re-created on the VPS whenever someone runs rsync with a trailing slash
# on `apps/` (which puts contents at /opt/labcontrol/{labwin_sync,studies,...}
# instead of /opt/labcontrol/apps/...). We saw this on 2026-05-09 — the new
# tasks.py landed at /opt/labcontrol/labwin_sync/tasks.py while the build kept
# using the stale /opt/labcontrol/apps/labwin_sync/tasks.py from a previous
# deploy. These excludes ensure the build context only ever uses the canonical
# apps/ layout, even if root fossils exist.
/analytics
/appointments
/core
/labwin_sync
/notifications
/payments
/studies
/users
